    "role": "user",
    "content": "## Theorem: translated_imo_2003_p4\n\nTheorem: translated_imo_2003_p4\nGiven: a b c = triangle a b c\nGiven: o = circle o a b c\nGiven: b1 = on_circle b1 o a, on_bline b1 c a\nGiven: d1 = on_circle d1 o a, on_bline d1 c a\nGiven: x = on_line x b b1, on_line x a c\nGiven: d = on_line d d1 x, on_circle d o a\nGiven: p = foot p d b c\nGiven: q = foot q d c a\nGiven: r = foot r d a b\nProve: prove that segment pq = segment qr\n\nGoal: cong p q q r\n\n## English proof (from stage 1)\n{\n  \"key_observation\": \"The points b1 and d1 are arc midpoints of AC on the circumcircle, so BB1 and DD1 are angle bisectors; this gives AD/DC = AB/BC, which together with the projection-distance formula gives PQ = QR.\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Show that BB1 and DD1 are angle bisectors of the relevant angles.\",\n    \"Use the angle-bisector theorem to relate AB/BC and AD/DC.\",\n    \"Use the sine rule in triangle ABC to rewrite AB/BC in terms of sin C and sin A.\",\n    \"Compute PQ and QR using the standard distance formula for orthogonal projections onto two intersecting lines.\",\n    \"Combine the equalities to conclude PQ = QR.\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The line BB1 is an angle bisector of angle ABC.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since b1 lies on the perpendicular bisector of CA, we have b1A = b1C. Since b1, A, B, C lie on the same circle, equal chords b1A and b1C subtend equal angles at B, so ∠ABb1 = ∠b1BC. Therefore BB1 bisects angle ABC, possibly as an internal or external angle bisector depending on the position of b1.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of perpendicular bisector\",\n        \"equal chords subtend equal inscribed angles\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The line DD1 is an angle bisector of angle ADC.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since d1 lies on the perpendicular bisector of CA, we have d1A = d1C. Since d1, A, D, C lie on the same circle, equal chords d1A and d1C subtend equal angles at D, so ∠ADd1 = ∠d1DC. Thus DD1 bisects angle ADC, possibly internally or externally.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of perpendicular bisector\",\n        \"equal chords subtend equal inscribed angles\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"AB/BC = AD/DC.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Because X lies on BB1 and on AC, step 1 and the angle-bisector theorem in triangle ABC give AX/XC = AB/BC, with directed lengths if X lies outside segment AC. Because X lies on DD1 and on AC, step 2 and the angle-bisector theorem in triangle ADC give AX/XC = AD/DC. Hence AB/BC = AD/DC.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"angle-bisector theorem\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"AD sin∠BAC = DC sin∠BCA.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By the sine rule in triangle ABC, AB/BC = sin∠BCA/sin∠BAC. Combining this with step 3 gives AD/DC = sin∠BCA/sin∠BAC. Multiplying both sides by DC sin∠BAC gives AD sin∠BAC = DC sin∠BCA.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 3\",\n        \"sine rule\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"For any point Y and two lines through a point V making angle θ, if F1 and F2 are the perpendicular projections of Y onto the two lines, then F1F2 = VY · sin θ.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Choose coordinates with V as the origin, the first line as the x-axis, and the second line making angle θ with the x-axis. If Y = ρ(cos φ, sin φ), then the projections are F1 = ρ cos φ · e1 and F2 = ρ cos(φ - θ) · e2, where e1 and e2 are unit vectors along the two lines. A direct calculation gives |F1F2|^2 = ρ^2 sin^2 θ, so F1F2 = VY · sin θ.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"orthogonal projection formula\",\n        \"coordinate distance formula\",\n        \"trigonometric identities\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"PQ = DC sin∠BCA.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Apply step 5 with V = C, Y = D, and the two lines CA and CB. The perpendicular projections of D onto CA and CB are Q and P respectively, so PQ = DC sin∠BCA.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 5\",\n        \"definition of foot of perpendicular\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"QR = AD sin∠BAC.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Apply step 5 with V = A, Y = D, and the two lines AC and AB. The perpendicular projections of D onto AC and AB are Q and R respectively, so QR = AD sin∠BAC.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 5\",\n        \"definition of foot of perpendicular\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"PQ = QR.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By step 6, PQ = DC sin∠BCA. By step 7, QR = AD sin∠BAC. Step 4 states that these two quantities are equal, hence PQ = QR.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"step 6\",\n        \"step 7\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": null\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
