    "content": "## Theorem: translated_imo_2007_p4\n\nTheorem: translated_imo_2007_p4\nGiven: a b c = triangle a b c\nGiven: o = circle o a b c\nGiven: r = on_circle r o a, on_bline r a b\nGiven: l = midpoint l c a\nGiven: k = midpoint k c b\nGiven: p = on_line p o k, on_line p c r\nGiven: q = on_line q o l, on_line q c r\nGiven: l1 = foot l1 l c r\nGiven: k1 = foot k1 k c r\nProve: prove that kk1/ll1 = rq/rp\n\nGoal: eqratio k k1 l l1 r q r p\n\n## English proof (from stage 1)\n{\n  \"key_observation\": \"Since R is the midpoint of arc AB, the line CR is the angle bisector at C, so a coordinate system with CR as the x-axis makes all needed lengths elementary to compute.\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Show that CR bisects angle ACB.\",\n    \"Place coordinates with C at the origin and CR as the x-axis.\",\n    \"Compute the midpoint coordinates of K and L and hence KK1/LL1.\",\n    \"Use the circumcircle equation to compute the circumcenter O.\",\n    \"Find the intersections P = OK ∩ CR and Q = OL ∩ CR.\",\n    \"Compare the resulting expressions for RQ/RP and KK1/LL1.\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The line CR bisects angle ACB, so ∠ACR = ∠RCB.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Because R lies on the perpendicular bisector of AB, we have RA = RB. Equal chords RA and RB in the circumcircle subtend equal inscribed angles at C, hence ∠ACR = ∠RCB.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of perpendicular bisector\",\n        \"equal chords subtend equal angles in a circle\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"We may choose coordinates C = (0,0), R = (rho,0), A = (u cos theta, u sin theta), and B = (v cos theta, -v sin theta), where u = CA, v = CB, and 0 < theta < pi/2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Take the x-axis to be the line CR. Since CR bisects angle ACB, the rays CA and CB make equal angles theta with CR on opposite sides of the x-axis. The distances from C to A and B are u and v, respectively.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"coordinate representation using polar coordinates\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The midpoints are L = ((u cos theta)/2, (u sin theta)/2) and K = ((v cos theta)/2, -(v sin theta)/2).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since C = (0,0), the midpoint of C and A is obtained by halving the coordinates of A, and the midpoint of C and B is obtained by halving the coordinates of B.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"midpoint formula\",\n        \"step 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"KK1 = (v sin theta)/2 and LL1 = (u sin theta)/2, hence KK1/LL1 = v/u.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The line CR is the x-axis, so the perpendicular distance from a point to CR is the absolute value of its y-coordinate. Thus KK1 is the absolute value of the y-coordinate of K, and LL1 is the absolute value of the y-coordinate of L.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"distance from a point to the x-axis\",\n        \"step 3\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The circumcircle of A, B, C, R has equation x^2 + y^2 - rho x + mu y = 0 for some real number mu.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since the circle passes through C = (0,0), its equation has no constant term. Since it also passes through R = (rho,0), substituting R gives rho^2 + D rho = 0, so the coefficient of x is D = -rho.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"general equation of a circle\",\n        \"step 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"rho = (u + v)/(2 cos theta) and mu = (v - u)/(2 sin theta).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Substituting A into the circle equation gives u^2 - rho u cos theta + mu u sin theta = 0, so u - rho cos theta + mu sin theta = 0. Substituting B gives v^2 - rho v cos theta - mu v sin theta = 0, so v - rho cos theta - mu sin theta = 0. Adding these two equations yields rho = (u + v)/(2 cos theta), and subtracting yields mu = (v - u)/(2 sin theta).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 5\",\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"algebra\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The circumcenter is O = ((u + v)/(4 cos theta), (u - v)/(4 sin theta)).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"For the circle x^2 + y^2 - rho x + mu y = 0, the center is (rho/2, -mu/2). Substituting the values of rho and mu from the previous step gives the stated coordinates.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"center of a circle from its equation\",\n        \"step 6\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The point P = OK ∩ CR has coordinates P = (v/(2 cos theta), 0).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Parametrize the line OK as O + t(K - O). Its y-coordinate is zero when t = -O_y/(K_y - O_y). Using O_y = (u - v)/(4 sin theta), K_y = -v sin theta/2, O_x = (u + v)/(4 cos theta), and K_x = v cos theta/2, this gives t = (v - u)/(v cos 2theta - u). Also K_x - O_x = (v cos 2theta - u)/(4 cos theta), so the x-coordinate is (u + v)/(4 cos theta) + (v - u)/(4 cos theta) = v/(2 cos theta).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 3\",\n        \"step 7\",\n        \"parametric equation of a line\",\n        \"trigonometric identity 2cos^2 theta - 1 = cos 2theta\",\n        \"algebra\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The point Q = OL ∩ CR has coordinates Q = (u/(2 cos theta), 0).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Parametrize the line OL as O + t(L - O). Its y-coordinate is zero when t = -O_y/(L_y - O_y). Using O_y = (u - v)/(4 sin theta), L_y = u sin theta/2, O_x = (u + v)/(4 cos theta), and L_x = u cos theta/2, one obtains t = (v - u)/(v - u cos 2theta). Since L_x - O_x = (u cos 2theta - v)/(4 cos theta), the x-coordinate is (u + v)/(4 cos theta) + (u - v)/(4 cos theta) = u/(2 cos theta).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 3\",\n        \"step 7\",\n        \"parametric equation of a line\",\n        \"trigonometric identity 2cos^2 theta - 1 = cos 2theta\",\n        \"algebra\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"RQ = v/(2 cos theta) and RP = u/(2 cos theta).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"From step 6, R = (rho,0) with rho = (u + v)/(2 cos theta). Since P and Q lie on the x-axis, RQ = rho - u/(2 cos theta) = v/(2 cos theta), and RP = rho - v/(2 cos theta) = u/(2 cos theta).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 6\",\n        \"step 8\",\n        \"step 9\",\n        \"distance on a coordinate line\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"KK1/LL1 = RQ/RP.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By step 4, KK1/LL1 = v/u. By step 10, RQ/RP = [v/(2 cos theta)]/[u/(2 cos theta)] = v/u. Therefore the two ratios are equal.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"step 10\",\n        \"algebra\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": null\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
