translation, rotation, and scaling\",\n        \"definition of tangent line\",\n        \"definition of reflection\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"There exist real numbers u and v with u != v such that K = (u/(1 + u^2), 1/(1 + u^2)) and L = (v/(1 + v^2), 1/(1 + v^2)).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Every point (x,y) != (0,0) on x^2 + y^2 = y has y != 0, so setting u = x/y gives x = uy. Substituting into the circle equation gives (u^2 + 1)y^2 = y, hence y = 1/(1 + u^2) and x = u/(1 + u^2). The same parametrization applies to L; nondegeneracy of triangle MLK gives u != v.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"parametrization of a circle through the origin\",\n        \"nondegeneracy of a triangle\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The reflected points B and C have coordinates B = (r + 2u/(1 + u^2), 2/(1 + u^2)) and C = (-r + 2v/(1 + v^2), 2/(1 + v^2)).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Because B is the reflection of P in K, the point K is the midpoint of PB, so B = 2K - P. Similarly, since C is the reflection of Q in L, we have C = 2L - Q.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of reflection\",\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"step 3\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The point A has coordinates A = (r(u + v)/(v - u), 2r/(v - u)).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The line BQ has direction B - Q = 2K, hence direction (u,1). The line CP has direction C - P = 2L, hence direction (v,1). Thus A = Q + lambda(u,1) = P + lambda(v,1), so comparing x-coordinates gives r + lambda u = -r + lambda v, hence lambda = 2r/(v - u).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"definition of collinearity\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Let O* = (0,z), where z = 1 + r(1 + uv)/(v - u), and define F(x,y) = x^2 + y^2 - 2zy. Then F(B) = r^2 - 4r/(v - u).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Using the coordinates of B, we get B_x^2 + B_y^2 = r^2 + 4ru/(1 + u^2) + 4/(1 + u^2). Therefore F(B) = r^2 + [4ru + 4 - 4z]/(1 + u^2). Since 1 - z = -r(1 + uv)/(v - u), this simplifies to r^2 + 4r[u(v - u) - (1 + uv)]/((v - u)(1 + u^2)) = r^2 - 4r/(v - u).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"algebraic simplification\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"With the same O* and F, one has F(C) = r^2 - 4r/(v - u).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Using the coordinates of C, we get C_x^2 + C_y^2 = r^2 - 4rv/(1 + v^2) + 4/(1 + v^2). Hence F(C) = r^2 + [-4rv + 4 - 4z]/(1 + v^2). Since 1 - z = -r(1 + uv)/(v - u), this becomes r^2 - 4r[v(v - u) + (1 + uv)]/((v - u)(1 + v^2)) = r^2 - 4r/(v - u).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"algebraic simplification\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"With the same O* and F, one has F(A) = r^2 - 4r/(v - u).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"From the coordinates of A, A_x^2 + A_y^2 = r^2((u + v)^2 + 4)/(v - u)^2 and A_y = 2r/(v - u). Thus F(A) = r^2((u + v)^2 + 4)/(v - u)^2 - 4rz/(v - u). Substituting z = 1 + r(1 + uv)/(v - u), we obtain F(A) = r^2((u + v)^2 + 4 - 4(1 + uv))/(v - u)^2 - 4r/(v - u) = r^2 - 4r/(v - u).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 5\",\n        \"algebraic simplification\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The point O* is the circumcenter of triangle ABC, so O = O*.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The equation F(x,y) = constant is equivalent to x^2 + (y - z)^2 = constant + z^2, which is a circle centered at O* = (0,z). Steps 6, 7, and 8 show that A, B, and C lie on this circle. Since O is defined as the circumcenter of A, B, C, uniqueness of the circumcenter gives O = O*.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"steps 6\",\n        \"step 7\",\n        \"step 8\",\n        \"equation of a circle\",\n        \"uniqueness of circumcenter\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"OP = OQ.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since O = O* = (0,z), P = (-r,0), and Q = (r,0), we have OP^2 = r^2 + z^2 and OQ^2 = r^2 + z^2. Hence OP = OQ.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"st