; then T(u) lies on the unit circle, T(0) = C, and the line through T(u) and T(v) has equation (uv - 1)x - (u + v)y + (uv + 1) = 0.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Substitution gives ((1-u^2)/(1+u^2))^2 + (2u/(1+u^2))^2 = 1, so T(u) lies on the unit circle. A line through two circle points has an equation whose substitution in the parameter r vanishes at r = u and r = v; expanding gives the stated equation.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"rational parametrization of the unit circle\",\n        \"equation of a line through two points\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"If A = T(alpha) and B = T(beta), then alpha and beta satisfy 2 alpha beta = t(alpha + beta).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since A, B, and S are collinear, S = (1,t) lies on the line through T(alpha) and T(beta). Substituting x = 1 and y = t into the chord equation gives (alpha beta - 1) - t(alpha + beta) + (alpha beta + 1) = 0, hence 2 alpha beta = t(alpha + beta).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"collinearity\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"If M = T(m), then P = (1 - 2mt/(1 + m^2), 2t/(1 + m^2)).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since C = T(0), M = T(m), and P are collinear, substituting u = 0 and v = m in the chord equation gives the line CM: x = 1 - my. Write P = (1 - my, y). The condition SP = SC gives (P_x - 1)^2 + (P_y - t)^2 = t^2, so m^2y^2 + (y - t)^2 = t^2, hence y((1 + m^2)y - 2t) = 0. Since P is not C in the nondegenerate configuration, y = 2t/(1 + m^2), giving the stated coordinates.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"definition of distance\",\n        \"hypothesis SC = SP\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Let K = T(k), L = T(l), and define D = 1 + m^2 - mt. Then k = t(alpha - m)/(D alpha - t) and l = t(beta - m)/(D beta - t).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since A, K, and P are collinear, P lies on the line through T(alpha) and T(k). Substituting the coordinates of P from step 4 into the chord equation and simplifying gives D alpha k - t(alpha + k) + mt = 0, hence k = t(alpha - m)/(D alpha - t). The same argument applied to B, L, and P gives l = t(beta - m)/(D beta - t).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"collinearity\",\n        \"algebra\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The parameters k and l satisfy (1 - m^2)(k + l) + 2m(kl - 1) = 0.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Let sigma = alpha + beta and pi = alpha beta. By step 3, t sigma = 2pi. From step 5, with Delta = (D alpha - t)(D beta - t), we get k + l = 2[pi(D(t - m) - t) + mt^2]/Delta and kl = [pi(t^2 - 2mt) + m^2t^2]/Delta, while Delta = pi(D^2 - 2D) + t^2. Substituting these expressions into (1 - m^2)(k + l) + 2m(kl - 1), the numerator becomes 2pi F, where F = (1 - m^2)(D(t - m) - t) + m(t^2 - 2mt - D^2 + 2D). Since D = 1 + m^2 - mt, one checks directly that D(t - m) - t = -m((m - t)^2 + 1) and t^2 - 2mt - D^2 + 2D = t^2 - 2mt + 1 - m^2(m - t)^2, so F = 0.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 3\",\n        \"step 5\",\n        \"algebraic simplification\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"For any real u and v, |T(u)T(v)|^2 = 4(u - v)^2/((1 + u^2)(1 + v^2)).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Subtracting the coordinate formulas for T(u) and T(v), squaring the two coordinate differences, and simplifying gives the stated expression.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"Euclidean distance formula\",\n        \"algebra\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"MK = ML.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By step 7, MK^2 - ML^2 equals 4/((1 + m^2)(1 + k^2)(1 + l^2)) times ((m - k)^2(1 + l^2) - (m - l)^2(1 + k^2)). The latter factor simplifies to (k - l)((1 - m^2)(k + l) + 2m(kl - 1)), which is 0 by step 6. Hence MK^2 = ML^2, and therefore MK = ML.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 6\",\n        \"step 7\",\n        \"algebra\",\n        \"nonnegativity of segment lengths\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ]