    "content": "## Theorem: translated_imo_2012_p1\n\nTheorem: translated_imo_2012_p1\nGiven: a b c = triangle a b c\nGiven: m l k j = excenter2 m l k j a b c\nGiven: f = on_line f m l, on_line f b j\nGiven: g = on_line g m k, on_line g c j\nGiven: s = on_line s f a, on_line s b c\nGiven: t = on_line t g a, on_line t c b\nProve: prove that segment ms = segment mt\n\nGoal: cong m s m t\n\n## English proof (from stage 1)\n{\n  \"key_observation\": \"After placing the excircle as the unit circle tangent to BC at the origin, the points F and G have exactly half the y-coordinate of A, so their projections through A to BC give opposite x-coordinates for S and T.\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Normalize the configuration by coordinates with M at the origin and BC as the x-axis.\",\n    \"Compute the tangency points K and L of the excircle with AB and AC.\",\n    \"Compute the coordinates of A, F, and G.\",\n    \"Use collinearity of A,F,S and A,G,T to find the x-coordinates of S and T.\",\n    \"Show that S and T are symmetric about M on line BC.\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"We may choose coordinates so that M=(0,0), J=(0,-1), B=(-p,0), and C=(q,0), where p,q>0.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since the excircle is tangent to BC at M, the radius JM is perpendicular to BC. A translation, rotation, and scaling preserve all incidences and ratios of lengths, so we may put BC on the x-axis, M at the origin, and take the excircle to be the unit circle centered at J=(0,-1). Because M lies on segment BC, write B=(-p,0) and C=(q,0) with p,q>0.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"coordinate normalization by similarity\",\n        \"radius to tangent line is perpendicular\",\n        \"definition of excircle tangency\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The excircle has equation x^2+(y+1)^2=1, and its tangency points with AB and AC are K=(-2p/(1+p^2),-2p^2/(1+p^2)) and L=(2q/(1+q^2),-2q^2/(1+q^2)), respectively.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"For L=(x,y), the conditions are x^2+(y+1)^2=1 and (x,y+1)·(x-q,y)=0, because JL is perpendicular to CL. Subtracting gives y=-qx, and substitution gives the nonzero solution x=2q/(1+q^2), y=-2q^2/(1+q^2). The computation for K using B=(-p,0) gives y=px and hence K=(-2p/(1+p^2),-2p^2/(1+p^2)).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"equation of a circle\",\n        \"radius to tangent line is perpendicular\",\n        \"dot product criterion for perpendicularity\",\n        \"step 1\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The vertex A has coordinates A=((q-p)/(1-pq), 2pq/(1-pq)).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Line AB passes through B and K, so its equation is (1-p^2)y=2p(x+p). Line AC passes through C and L, so its equation is (q^2-1)y=2q(x-q). Solving these two linear equations gives y=2pq/(1-pq) and x=(q-p)/(1-pq); the denominator is nonzero because A is a finite vertex of the triangle.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"two-point equation of a line\",\n        \"solving simultaneous linear equations\",\n        \"step 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The point F=ML∩BJ has coordinates F=(-p/(1-pq), pq/(1-pq)).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since M=(0,0) and L lies on the line y=-qx, the line ML has equation y=-qx. The line BJ through B=(-p,0) and J=(0,-1) has equation y=-x/p-1. Solving -qx=-x/p-1 gives x=-p/(1-pq), and then y=pq/(1-pq).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"two-point equation of a line\",\n        \"solving simultaneous linear equations\",\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The point G=MK∩CJ has coordinates G=(q/(1-pq), pq/(1-pq)).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since M=(0,0) and K lies on the line y=px, the line MK has equation y=px. The line CJ through C=(q,0) and J=(0,-1) has equation y=x/q-1. Solving px=x/q-1 gives x=q/(1-pq), and then y=pq/(1-pq).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"two-point equation of a line\",\n        \"solving simultaneous linear equations\",\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The point S=AF∩BC has coordinates S=(-(p+q)/(1-pq),0).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Let h=pq/(1-pq). From steps 3 and 4, A has y-coordinate 2h and F has y-coordinate h. Since S lies on BC, its y-coordinate is 0, and since A,F,S are collinear, F is the midpoint of segment AS in affine coordinates; therefore x_S=2x_F-x_A. Substituting x_F=-p/(1-pq) and x_A=(q-p)/(1-pq) gives x_S=-(p+q)/(1-pq).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"collinearity\",\n        \"affine coordinates on a line\",\n        \"step 3\",\n        \"step 4\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The point T=AG∩BC has coordinates T=((p+q)/(1-pq),0).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Again let h=pq/(1-pq). From steps 3 and 5, A has y-coordinate 2h and G has y-coordinate h. Since T lies on BC and A,G,T are collinear, G is the midpoint of segment AT in affine coordinates; hence x_T=2x_G-x_A. Substituting x_G=q/(1-pq) and x_A=(q-p)/(1-pq) gives x_T=(p+q)/(1-pq).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"collinearity\",\n        \"affine coordinates on a line\",\n        \"step 3\",\n        \"step 5\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"MS=MT.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By steps 6 and 7, S and T lie on the x-axis with opposite x-coordinates, while M=(0,0). Therefore M is the midpoint of ST, and in particular the segment lengths MS and MT are equal.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"distance formula on a coordinate line\",\n        \"definition of midpoint\",\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 6\",\n        \"step 7\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": null\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
