s H=(u,u(1-u)/v).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of orthocenter\",\n        \"perpendicular slopes\",\n        \"step 1\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The point N is N=(u^2/(u^2+v^2), uv/(u^2+v^2)).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The point N lies on AB and on HC. Since HC is an altitude, HC is perpendicular to AB, so N is the foot of the perpendicular from C to line AB. The projection of C=(1,0) onto the line through the origin in direction A=(u,v) is ((C dot A)/(A dot A))A = (u/(u^2+v^2))(u,v).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of altitude\",\n        \"orthogonal projection formula\",\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The point M is M=(v^2/((1-u)^2+v^2), v(1-u)/((1-u)^2+v^2)).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The point M lies on AC and on HB. Since HB is an altitude, HB is perpendicular to AC, so M is the foot of the perpendicular from B to line AC. Writing AC with base C=(1,0) and direction A-C=(u-1,v), the projection parameter of B-C=(-1,0) onto A-C is (1-u)/((1-u)^2+v^2), giving the stated coordinates.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of altitude\",\n        \"orthogonal projection formula\",\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"If the circle through B,N,W has equation x^2+y^2-sx+Ey=0, then X=(0,-E).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Because the circle passes through B=(0,0), its constant term is 0. Because it passes through W=(s,0), the coefficient of x is -s. Its center is therefore O1=(s/2,-E/2). Since X lies on line O1W and on the circle as the point opposite W, X is the reflection of W in O1, hence X=2O1-W=(0,-E).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"standard equation of a circle\",\n        \"center of a circle from its equation\",\n        \"diameter endpoints are collinear with the center\",\n        \"step 1\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The coordinate of X is X=(0, u(1-s)/v).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Substituting N=(n_x,n_y) into x^2+y^2-sx+Ey=0 gives -E=(n_x^2+n_y^2-sn_x)/n_y. From step 3, n_x=u^2/(u^2+v^2), n_y=uv/(u^2+v^2), and n_x^2+n_y^2=u^2/(u^2+v^2). Therefore -E=(u^2(1-s)/(u^2+v^2))/(uv/(u^2+v^2))=u(1-s)/v.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 3\",\n        \"step 5\",\n        \"algebraic simplification\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"If the circle through C,M,W has equation x^2+y^2-(s+1)x+E'y+s=0, then Y=(1,-E').\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"For y=0, the circle meets the x-axis at x=s and x=1, so the quadratic part on the x-axis is (x-s)(x-1)=x^2-(s+1)x+s. Thus the center is O2=((s+1)/2,-E'/2). Since Y is the point opposite W on this circle, Y=2O2-W=(1,-E').\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"standard equation of a circle\",\n        \"center of a circle from its equation\",\n        \"diameter endpoints are collinear with the center\",\n        \"step 1\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The coordinate of Y is Y=(1, s(1-u)/v).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Substituting M=(m_x,m_y) into x^2+y^2-(s+1)x+E'y+s=0 gives -E'=(m_x^2+m_y^2-(s+1)m_x+s)/m_y. From step 4, with T=(1-u)^2+v^2, we have m_x=v^2/T, m_y=v(1-u)/T, and m_x^2+m_y^2=v^2/T. Hence -E'=(v^2/T-(s+1)v^2/T+s)/(v(1-u)/T)=s(1-u)/v.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"step 7\",\n        \"algebraic simplification\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The points X,H,Y are collinear.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"From steps 6 and 8, X=(0,u(1-s)/v) and Y=(1,s(1-u)/v). The point on line XY with x-coordinate u has y-coordinate (1-u)(u(1-s)/v)+u(s(1-u)/v)=u(1-u)/v. By step 2, this is exactly the y-coordinate of H, so H lies on line XY.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"two-point equation of a line\",\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"step 6\",\n        \"step 8\",\n        \"algebraic simplification\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": null\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
