P/sin C = c/sin A. Using the sine rule in triangle ABC, c/sin C = a/sin A, hence BP = c^2/a.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"given angle equality for P\",\n        \"P lies on line BC\",\n        \"angle sum in a triangle\",\n        \"sine rule\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The point Q has coordinates Q = ((a^2 - b^2)/a,0).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since Q lies on line BC and angle CAQ equals angle CBA, triangle ACQ has angles angle CAQ = angle CBA and angle ACQ = angle ACB. Hence its third angle equals angle BAC. By the sine rule in triangle ACQ, CQ/sin(angle CAQ) = AC/sin(angle AQC), so CQ/sin B = b/sin A. Using the sine rule in triangle ABC, b/sin B = a/sin A, hence CQ = b^2/a. Therefore BQ = BC - CQ = a - b^2/a = (a^2 - b^2)/a.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"given angle equality for Q\",\n        \"Q lies on line BC\",\n        \"angle sum in a triangle\",\n        \"sine rule\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The reflected points are M = (2c^2/a - u,-v) and N = (2(a^2-b^2)/a - u,-v).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Because M is the reflection of A in P, the point P is the midpoint of AM, so M = 2P - A. Similarly, because N is the reflection of A in Q, the point Q is the midpoint of AN, so N = 2Q - A.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of reflection in a point\",\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"step 3\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"If X = BM intersect CN, then X = tM with t = a^2/(2b^2 + 2c^2 - a^2).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since B = (0,0), every point on BM has the form tM. Write M = (m,-v), where m = 2c^2/a - u. Since C = (a,0), every point on CN has the form C + s(N-C). Comparing y-coordinates gives s = t. Comparing x-coordinates gives tm = a + t(N_x-a), so t(m - N_x + a) = a. Now m - N_x + a = 2c^2/a - 2(a^2-b^2)/a + a = (2b^2 + 2c^2 - a^2)/a, hence t = a^2/(2b^2 + 2c^2 - a^2).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"equation of a line through two points\",\n        \"step 4\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The circumcircle of ABC has equation x^2 + y^2 - ax + lambda y = 0, where lambda = (au - c^2)/v.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Any circle through B = (0,0) has equation x^2 + y^2 + Dx + Ey = 0. Since it also passes through C = (a,0), we get a^2 + Da = 0, hence D = -a. Since it passes through A = (u,v), we have u^2 + v^2 - au + lambda v = 0. Because u^2 + v^2 = c^2, this gives lambda = (au - c^2)/v.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"general equation of a circle\",\n        \"step 1\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"For m = 2c^2/a - u, one has m^2 + v^2 = c^2(2b^2 + 2c^2 - a^2)/a^2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Using u^2 + v^2 = c^2, we compute m^2 + v^2 = (2c^2/a - u)^2 + v^2 = 4c^4/a^2 - 4c^2u/a + c^2. Substituting u = (a^2 + c^2 - b^2)/(2a), this becomes c^2(4c^2/a^2 - 2(a^2+c^2-b^2)/a^2 + 1) = c^2(2b^2 + 2c^2 - a^2)/a^2.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"algebra\",\n        \"step 1\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The point X lies on the circumcircle of ABC.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By step 5, X = (tm,-tv), where t = a^2/(2b^2+2c^2-a^2). Substituting X into the circle equation from step 6 gives t^2(m^2+v^2) - atm - lambda tv = t(t(m^2+v^2) - am - lambda v). Since lambda v = au - c^2 and m = 2c^2/a - u, we have am + lambda v = a(2c^2/a-u) + au - c^2 = c^2. Thus the circle expression equals t(t(m^2+v^2)-c^2). By step 7 and the value of t, t(m^2+v^2) = c^2, so the expression is 0.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 5\",\n        \"step 6\",\n        \"step 7\",\n        \"algebra\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"OX = OA.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The point O is the circumcenter of triangle ABC. Since X lies on the circumcircle of ABC, its distance from O equals the common radius of the circumcircle, which is also OA.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of circumcenter\",\n        \"step 8\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": null\n}\n\